Summary of Ethereum block-building research as of 2024-08-07:

* Everyone agrees that having multiple actors contribute txs that must be included in the block is a good idea
* Open debate on whether avoiding a "last mover" is possible

It's good to see the progress! It feels like the block construction topic is nearing a light at the end of the tunnel.

result.text:
Definitely true that inclusion lists and BRAID have a lot in common

The things I like about Max's proposal that aren't in FOCIL:

* Priority ordering of txes rather than leader's discretion (allowing inclusion-list transactions to be MEV-relevant)
* Conditional tips (possibly making non-censorship incentive-compatible)
* No single assigned leader who is last mover (so at least the potential for no timing advantage)

Whatever you want to label this constellation of properties, I find it appealing

I interviewed @VitalikButerin (and the 80,000 Hours Podcast does video now). Topics:

• AI regulation disagreements are less about AI in particular, and more about whether you intuitively fear government power
• Whether the social impact of crypto has been disappointing
• Why his p(doom) has gone down
• How to trustlessly identify what everyone will agree is misinformation
• How he built so much consensus around def/acc (defensive acceleration)
• The defensive tech we most desperately need to accelerate
• His updated take on effective altruism
• Wei Dei's critique of Vitalik's 'My techno-optimism'

(First episode recorded in person! Let us know what you think and how it could be better.)

legacy.full_text: The right to have a private conversation, online or offline, is a bedrock human rights principle. https://t.co/kq3hW7W7nV
Recent news of EU chat control proposals failing feels like a significant win. Really grateful to see so many people working hard to make this outcome happen, and congratulations to Europeans.

(And yes I know it's not "dead". Realistically, it never will be. We're entering very challenging territory for preserving privacy, especially as things like mind reading become possible over the next century. No solution other than "eternal vigilance". Keep up the good fight!)

Prediction markets and Community Notes are becoming the two flagship social epistemic technologies of the 2020s.

Both truth-seeking and democratic, built around open public participation rather than pre-selected elites.

I want to see many more things like this.
